1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpb=
mtfaWQiOjIwMjI4MDV9/6b917cd53a1faebaf7f3928ef27256aa31a10c3b474c160ca087bb2=
266bc73c1" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">noted</a>, is=
 why <em>Trump</em> agreed to settle for a relative pittance, instead of pu=
tting the wood to Iger and ABC at trial.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The stated mot=
ivations are all true, to be sure, but the <em>Times </em>and <em>Journal <=
/em>pieces glossed
over one <em>other</em> key consideration. On Friday, the judge in the case=
, <strong>Cecilia M. Altonaga</strong>, ordered depositions of both Trump a=
nd Stephanopoulos, and ruled that Disney must produce all relevant text mes=
sages and emails sent to and from the ABC News anchor. According to well-pl=
aced sources at Disney and close to Stephanopoulos, there was extremely hig=
h concern among leadership over the release of Stephanopoulos=E2=80=99s cor=
respondence and how it might expose the anchor, the news
network, and the parent company to greater scrutiny. =E2=80=9CHe is sloppy =
electronically,=E2=80=9D one source said of Stephanopoulos. =E2=80=9CThey d=
idn=E2=80=99t want the phone going into discovery.=E2=80=9D (Of course, Dis=
ney has had its share of Stephanopoulos-related controversies, including th=
e disclosure of a $75,000 contribution to the Clinton Foundation in 2015 an=
d his off-the-cuff remark earlier this year about <strong>Biden</strong>=E2=
=80=99s fitness for office.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:
0;margin-bottom:0px;">Coincidentally, an ABC News spokesperson told me toda=
y that Stephanopoulos has <em>just</em> signed a new, multiyear contract wi=
th the network, unrelated to the timing of the settlement. Several insiders=
 speculated that Stephanopoulos=E2=80=99s new deal includes a pay cut, and =
noted that he is likely to <em>eventually</em> take on a more limited role,=
 after already ceding pole-anchor position on special event coverage to <st=
rong>David Muir</strong>. Disney is trying to lower costs
across its linear portfolio, including at ABC=E2=80=99s <em>Good Morning Am=
erica</em>, where Stephanopoulos and his co-anchors <strong>Robin Roberts <=
/strong>and <strong>Michael Strahan </strong>have historically made around =
$25 million a year=E2=80=94a gross misalignment of funds, given the declini=
ng audience for morning television, generally, and particularly in light of=
 <em>GMA</em>=E2=80=99s ratings slide since <strong>Almin Karamehmedovic </=
strong>became president of ABC News. Presumably, Stephanopoulos=E2=80=99s h=
eir
apparent, <strong>Whit Johnson</strong>, would deliver similar ratings and =
cost a <em>lot </em>less.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Indeed, that is where things seem to be h=
eaded=E2=80=94albeit with the discretion and diplomatic finesse befitting a=
 revered network veteran who, despite his slip-ups, has earned the right to=
 an elegant exit. Also, as you all know, television news is a business wher=
ein executives and talent air kiss each other
at lunch but complain ceaselessly about one another in private=E2=80=94thei=
r own version of being =E2=80=9Celectronically sloppy.=E2=80=9D George may =
be headed toward his next act as a public figure, but no one wants to be th=
e person responsible for it.</p></div>
